# Patisserie Write-up

Challenge: `Patisserie`
Category: `Web`
Points: `110`

## Summary

The app is split into:

- A Flask proxy that inspects the raw `Cookie` header and blocks any cookie name containing `admin`
- An Express backend that grants admin access when `req.cookies.is_admin === “1”`

The bug is a parser differential between Python’s `http.cookies.SimpleCookie` and Node’s cookie parser. A quoted cookie value containing semicolons is treated by the proxy as one harmless cookie, but Express splits it into multiple cookies and sees `is_admin=1`.

## Relevant Code

Proxy cookie filter:

- [app.py](/home/kali/patisserie/proxy/app.py#L24)

The proxy:

- parses the incoming `Cookie` header with `SimpleCookie`
- rejects the request only if a parsed cookie name contains `admin`
- forwards the original `Cookie` header unchanged to the backend

           Backend admin check:

- [index.js](/home/kali/patisserie/app/index.js#L250)

The backend returns the flag if:

```js
req.cookies.is_admin === “1”
```

## Exploit

Send a cookie header where the dangerous cookie is hidden inside a quoted value:

```bash
curl -H ‘Cookie: foo=”bar; is_admin=1; x=y”’ \
http://35.194.108.145:11198/admin
```

Why this works:

- Python `SimpleCookie` parses the header as a single cookie named `foo`
- The proxy sees no cookie name containing `admin`, so it forwards the request
- Node’s cookie parser splits on the embedded semicolons and treats `is_admin=1` as a real cookie
- The backend admin check passes and the flag is shown

